{"questionId":"9071897","questionHtml":"<p>Consider the standard electrode potentials:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:150px;\">Cr<sup>3+</sup> (aq) + 3e<sup>−</sup> <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" \\rightleftharpoons \">\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">⇌</mo>\n</math></span> Cr (s)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>E</em></strong><sup>Θ</sup> = −0.74 V</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:150px;\">Hg<sup>2+</sup> (aq) + 2e<sup>−</sup>&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" \\rightleftharpoons \">\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">⇌</mo>\n</math></span> Hg (l)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>E</em></strong><sup>Θ</sup>&nbsp;= +0.85 V</p>\n<p>What is the cell potential, in V, for the voltaic cell?</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:150px;\">2Cr (s) + 3Hg<sup>2+</sup> (aq) → 3Hg (l) + 2Cr<sup>3+</sup> (aq)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A.&nbsp; &nbsp;−1.59</p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; &nbsp;+0.11</p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; &nbsp;+1.07</p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; &nbsp;+1.59</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>D</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9071897","referenceCode":"18N.1.hl.TZ0.31","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Consider the standard electrode potentials: Cr3+ (aq) + 3e− ⇌ Cr (s) EΘ = −0.74 V Hg2+ (aq) + 2e− ⇌ Hg (l) EΘ = +0.85 V What is the cell potential, in V, for the voltaic cell? 2Cr ","paper":"1","level":"hl","questionNumber":"31","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 19: Redox processes","19.1 Electrochemical cells","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 19: Redox processes"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}